# 4. Lag Selection Is Not Sufficiently Justified

## Current Method

The notebook appears to retain lags when:

```python
abs(correlation) > 0.1
```

for at least 50% of brands.

## Problems

The threshold:

```text
|r| > 0.1
```

is arbitrary.

It does not account for:

- serial dependence
- sample size
- multiple testing
- series heterogeneity
- incremental predictive value
- collinearity between lags
- future-data leakage
- incorrect brand-level ordering

Highly persistent time series naturally produce correlations for many lags, even when those lags do not improve out-of-sample forecasts.

## Better Approach

Use theoretically and operationally plausible lag candidates.

For monthly sales, a reasonable starting set is:

```text
lag 1
lag 2
lag 3
lag 6
lag 12
```

These represent:

- immediate persistence
- short-term momentum
- quarterly memory
- half-year effects
- annual seasonality

Then compare feature groups using rolling-origin validation.

Example candidate sets:

```text
Recent:
lag 1
```

```text
Short-term:
lag 1, lag 2, lag 3
```

```text
Seasonal:
lag 1, lag 3, lag 12
```

```text
Extended:
lag 1, lag 2, lag 3, lag 6, lag 12
```

A lag set should be retained only when it produces consistent out-of-sample improvement over simpler alternatives.

Pairwise in-sample correlation alone is not sufficient justification.

