# 10. Train-Validation-Test Split Requires Stronger Justification

## Current Split

The notebook appears to use:

```text
24 months training
6 months validation
14 months testing
```

with a maximum rolling warm-up of approximately 13 periods.

## Problem

With 24 training months and a 13-month warm-up, only approximately 11 fully usable training observations remain for a complete series.

Late-entry series may have considerably fewer.

At the same time, 14 months are reserved for testing, which is a large proportion of a 44-month dataset.

A single six-month validation period also makes model selection highly dependent on one specific seasonal segment.

## Recommended Evaluation Strategy

Use:

- one final untouched test period
- multiple rolling-origin validation folds before the test period

Example:

```text
Fold 1:
Train through month 24
Validate months 25–27

Fold 2:
Train through month 27
Validate months 28–30

Fold 3:
Train through month 30
Validate months 31–33

Final test:
Last 6–12 months
```

The exact design should depend on the operational forecast horizon.

## Horizon Alignment

If the business predicts one month ahead:

```text
evaluate repeated one-step-ahead forecasts
```

If the business predicts three months ahead:

```text
evaluate horizon 1, horizon 2, and horizon 3 separately
```

Validation must reproduce how forecasts will be generated in production.

## Expanding vs Fixed Training Window

Two possible approaches are:

### Expanding Window

All prior observations are retained.

Advantages:

- more training data
- suitable when older relationships remain relevant

### Fixed-Length Window

Only the most recent observations are retained.

Advantages:

- better adaptation to structural change
- reduced influence of outdated patterns

The choice should be evaluated empirically.

